<center>Druid of the 60th Ring <br>
<center> Resident of The Tribunal <br></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=wenin>Wenin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I read boards more<br>than I play EQ....</span><br>  Posts: 848<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(12/31/02 4:31 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=309.topic&index=71>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.aradcliff.net/images/130.gif width=128 height=80></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: ...</span><hr size=1> It is your &quot;opinion&quot; that it is smoke and mirrors.  Ok, fine.  You can have that, but I'm have to ask why you do?<br>
<br>
how do you explain:<br>
<br>
- scientists that have come forth in the past (before 9-11) and spoke of the nuclear weapon research? They lying?<br>
- The shipments that have been reported to have arrived in Iraq.  Shipments where they said the items were for use in X area, but could also be used in the creation of WMD.  The shipments are fictious?<br>
- The scientists being questioned now, are being questioned inside Iraq, where their families live.  Do you expect them to come forth and rat out their government, even if they were not willing to lie about their hidden research to begin with?<br>
<br>
For Iraq to be smoke and mirrors you have to believe that Iraq is telling the truth, and the US government has been lying.  While we have information to show that Iraq isn't all that truthful with the international community, we don't have any evidence that the information presented against Iraq has been made up.  Well, unless you read conspiracy theorist websites.  (not claiming you do, I just know they exist)<br>
<br>
I don't know the numbers NK has in military strength, and I'm not going to say that you've made those numbers up. I'd like to know where you got them and how old they are.  1.2 Million is a surprisingly high count of troops, but not unbelievable.<br>
<br>
As for negoitations, they've failed, in both situations.  We dealt with North Korea fairly, and they have shown to have given us the shaft.  We've been dealing with Iraq for over 10 years now, they are just now finally doing what they should have done 10 years ago.<br>
<br>
What brought upon their changes in attitude?<br>
<br>
What brought Iraq to finally comply?<br>
<br>
It is my belief that they have for one of two reasons.<br>
1.  They want to take us for another round around the mulberry bush.<br>
2.  They are finally complying with the agreements they signed and agreed to over 10 years ago.<br>
a. Because they saw the error of their ways, and have changed.<br>
b. Because of the sanctions placed on them, can no longer pursue their goals.<br>
<br>
I'm betting on 2b, personally.<br>
<br>
What brought NK to the decision to make their actions public?<br>
<br>
They saw the US wrapped up with the Iraq/Terrorism/Afghanistan/Pakistan situation.  How could we handle another?  With our plate so full, it's an excellent oppurtunity for them to &quot;renegotiate&quot; their contract with us.  They are the ones creating the pressure there, not us.  We were FINE with how things were in NK.  Sure they weren't perfect, but far better than they are now.<br>
<br>
Also, what exactly can we do against North Korea?  We had shipments of Oil or something to them right?  Ok, we stopped those over a month ago, right?  What is left to what we could do?  Ask them politely to stop?  Why would they, what reasons do they have to do so?  Have they made their &quot;demands&quot; public?  There is all kind of talk about them wanting &quot;dialogue&quot;.  To talk about what?  They want MORE appeasment.  They are using their nuclear program like a gun to our heads.  It's a threat, and we all know that.  Nukes aren't built primarily for DEFENSE, like Merton has suggested.  They are offensive weapons.  The only time that a country would use a nuke for defensive purposes is if they are loosing or about to loose a war.  Where they would need to nuke an invading army.  Who has threatened to invade North Korea?  No one.  They are the ones that have been thumping their chests for almost a half century towards South Korea.  They do it so often the South Koreans have gotten use to them to the point that the threats are ignored.<br>
<br>
North Korea has one card to play, in order to get MORE support from the international community.  They are playing it.<br>
<br>
What is there to do about North Korea?<br>
<br>
Loegan, I know you're not a &quot;Dove&quot;.<br>
<br>
